{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a7335f99-1d6c-4b73-921f-c3100e6f53a8","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** I tested it on .NET 10 and it compiled and ran without issues:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  signedSpan   = stackalloc nint[4];\nSpan<nuint> unsignedSpan = stackalloc nuint[4];\n```\n\nOutput confirmed:\n- `nint` size: **8 bytes** (on this 64-bit system)\n- Both `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>` worked correctly, including storing `nint.MaxValue` / `nuint.MaxValue`.\n\nNote: you need `<AllowUnsafeBlocks>true</AllowUnsafeBlocks>` in your project since `stackalloc` requires an unsafe context (unless assigned directly to a `Span<T>`, which is the implicit-safe form used here — but the project property is still required).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82f6d793-8ba3-4024-a3fd-2fdedf2e6406","outputTokens":240},"id":"abc6539e-4a80-42b4-8d46-ec073c36322f","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:41:27.351Z","parentId":"3ea13c85-78f7-4177-aa5e-f07d54a8086a"}
